{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17636188","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17636188"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:25:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:25:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17572"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17572","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17572"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10262"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71345"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10262","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10262"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17572"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56820"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10057"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23975"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23983"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71345","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71345"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe liver is a metabolically active organ that requires significant energy production to maintain its various functions including protein synthesis, bile production, and glucose regulation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of ATP production in hepatocytes?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Substrate-level phosphorylation","Glycogenolysis","Oxidative phosphorylation in mitochondria","Beta-oxidation of fatty acids only","Anaerobic glycolysis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary mechanism of ATP production in hepatocytes is \u003Cstrong\u003Eoxidative phosphorylation in mitochondria\u003C/strong\u003E. This process occurs in the numerous mitochondria present in liver cells and provides the majority of cellular ATP through the electron transport chain and chemiosmosis. The liver\u0027s rich blood supply delivers oxygen and nutrients needed to support this aerobic process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnaerobic glycolysis\u003C/strong\u003E - This is a less efficient process that produces only 2 ATP per glucose molecule and is not the primary energy source in well-oxygenated hepatocytes\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubstrate-level phosphorylation\u003C/strong\u003E - While this occurs during glycolysis and the citric acid cycle, it produces much less ATP than oxidative phosphorylation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBeta-oxidation of fatty acids only\u003C/strong\u003E - While beta-oxidation occurs in hepatocytes, it feeds into the electron transport chain rather than directly producing ATP\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlycogenolysis\u003C/strong\u003E - This process breaks down glycogen to glucose but does not directly produce ATP\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe liver\u0027s high energy demands require efficient ATP production through oxidative phosphorylation, which produces approximately 36 ATP molecules per glucose molecule metabolised.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The liver produces ATP primarily through oxidative phosphorylation in mitochondria using nutrients from the portal circulation.","The liver maintains high ATP production even during fasting due to its essential metabolic functions.","Hepatocytes contain abundant mitochondria to support their high energy demands."],"references":["Hall J. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2021. Available from: https://clinicalkeymeded.elsevier.com/reader/books/9780323597128"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56820"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17572"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56820","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56820"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-18T07:48:03+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-18T07:48:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10262"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71345"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4928"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udca9","name":"Gastrointestinal","synonyms":[],"description":null